04676nam a22006615i 9780226383927DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016053327  a97802263839277 a10.7208/97802263839272doi  a(DE-B1597)550228  a(OCoLC)995769927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aLB2351.5b.T66 2017 4aLB2351 7aLAN0000002bisacsh04a378.1/6161 aToor, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWrite Your Way In :bCrafting an Unforgettable College Admissions Essay /cRachel Toor. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (164 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChicago Guides to Writing, Editing, and Publishing00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPart One What You Need to Know Before You Start Writing -- t1: Steal, Steal, Steal: Learning to Read like a Writer -- t2: Craft Your “I”: -- t3: Sex, Drugs, and Palestinian Statehood -- tAMANDA + JIM -- t4: Aboutness -- tADAM FINDS HIS PIRATES -- t5: The Hole in the Donut -- t6: Tell Us About Your World in Two Hundred Words -- tEMMA’S SHORTIES -- tPart Two Getting It Down on the Page and Then Cleaning It Up -- t7: Shitty First Drafts -- t8: Seeing Again -- t9: Don’t Try to Hook the Reader like a Trout -- tPEYTON’S ANKLE -- t10: Danger! -- t11: Semicolons Are like Loaded Guns -- t12: My Little Bag of Writing Tricks -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWriting, for most of us, is bound up with anxiety. It’s even worse when it feels like your whole future—or at least where you’ll spend the next four years in college—is on the line. It’s easy to understand why so many high school seniors put off working on their applications until the last minute or end up with a generic and clichéd essay. The good news? You already have the “secret sauce” for crafting a compelling personal essay: your own experiences and your unique voice. The best essays rarely catalog how students have succeeded or achieved. Good writing shows the reader how you’ve struggled and describes mistakes you’ve made. Excellent essays express what you’re fired up about, illustrate how you think, and illuminate the ways you’ve grown. More than twenty million students apply to college every year; many of them look similar in terms of test scores, grades, courses taken, extracurricular activities. Admissions officers wade through piles of files. As an applicant, you need to think about what will interest an exhausted reader. What can you write that will make her argue to admit you instead of the thousands of other applicants? A good essay will be conversational and rich in vivid details, and it could only be written by one person—you. This book will help you figure out how to find and present the best in yourself. You’ll acquire some useful tools for writing well—and may even have fun—in the process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCollege applicationszUnited States. 0aCreative writing. 0aEssayxAuthorship. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdmission. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  acollege admissions.  acollege application essays.  aelite college admissions.  aivy league.  amemoir.  apersonal essays.  aundergraduate admissions.  awriting mistakes.  awriting tips.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226383927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226383927.jpg  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles